That is very true.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="18" relname="span"> Today, there is a lot of new technology out there.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="17" relname="span"> There are devices that can be used for more than one thing.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="16" relname="span"> How to use them all is what gets customers frustrated.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="14" relname="background"> I used to work for Nokia Mobile Phones and they had a device called a Communicator.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="10" relname="concession"> It was a nice device,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="14" relname="span"> but it was hard to remember how to do certain things.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="11" relname="volitional-cause"> We used to have customers call in</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="12" relname="span"> because they could not remember how to do a particular function.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="10" relname="elaboration"> Even us, as the support team, sometimes had trouble remembering certain features that were not commonly used.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="17" relname="evaluation"> 
This is something that should be thought about when designing products.</segment>
